# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Seemed Truly Easy At First, Turned Out To Be Easier.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The Approach Taken Is Explained Below :-

(1) Initialise A Single Dimensional Array Of Size m*n and Pass Each Value Of The Matrix Sequentially Into The Single Dimensional Array.

(2) Rotate The Array K Times Using The Following Algorithm :-

Step (i) - Reverse The Entire Array
Step (ii) - Reverse The First K Elements (From Indexes 0 To K-1)
Step (iii) - Reverse The Rest of The Elements (From Indexes K To arr.length-1)

(3) Store Each Element Of The Rotated Array In an ArrayList Of Size Equal To Number of Columns In Each Row. After Each Row, Pass The ArrayList Into an ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> Which Will Hold The Values Of All Rows Respectively.

(4) Return The ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>>.

Good Luck!

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(m*n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(m*n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

