solutions.content:
**Solution using 1-D array Rotation Tricks in the 2-D Like we Did in *Search in 2-D Matrix* (Binary Search Solution)**

**TC :** ***O(n x m)***
**SC :** ***O(1)***


```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> shiftGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        int n = grid. size(), m = grid[0].size();
        vector<vector<int>> resGrid(n,vector<int> (m));
        int total = n * m; //total distance we need to move is this
        for(int i = 0; i< total ; i++){
          int row = i/m, col = i%m;//easy trick to find indices via 1-D array trick in 2-D arrays

         /*now if the value shifts to the k times then for K > N*M we need to do k  % total 
		 taking example of K = 3 and n = 3 , m= 3 then for index (i = 8) in 1-D 
		 will equal to (i = 8+3 =11) which crosses the n*m(total) so for preventing this rotation we do modulo */

			int shift = (i+k)%total;  /*this is the final place (for 1-D representation where value need to 
			be shift now this the index in 1-D representationnow again we need to 
			find the right index for 2-D grid via 1-D array using same operation as we did above)*/
            int newRow = shift/m , newCol = shift%m;

			//put these values after shifting into the grid
            resGrid[newRow][newCol] = grid[row][col];
        }
        return resGrid;
    }
};
```

