solutions.content:
It consists of two concepts:
1. In-place array shifting/rotating can be decomposed into 3 reverse operations.
	e.x.
		[1, 2, 3, 4, 5] right rotate 2  => [4, 5, 1, 2, 3]
	equals to 
		[1, 2, 3, 4, 5] reverse  =>  [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] reverse first 2  => [<u>4, 5</u>, 3, 2, 1] reverse rest of the elements  =>  [4, 5, <u>1, 2, 3</u>]
2. The coordinate conversion between 1D and 2D can be achieved by '/' and '%' operators with the width n of the 2D matrix.
```
void reverse(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int n, int a, int b)
{
	int ix, iy, jx, jy;

	for (int i = a, j = b; i < j; ++i, --j)
	{
		ix = i / n;
		iy = i % n;
		jx = j / n;
		jy = j % n;

		swap(grid[ix][iy], grid[jx][jy]);
	}
}

